events.name: 3D Printing on the PolyPrinter
events.description:
3D printing has become the modern way to create, prototype, and prepare your parts before moving them onto mass manufacturing processes. From a 3D computer model, real objects are fabricated in a number of methods.
In this two hour class, you will learn how to import, prepare and print your three-dimensional parts using the PolyPrinter 229 3D printer.
Pre-Requisites
None
You will learn

The theory of Fused Deposition Modeling (FDM) 3D printing
The various parts of the PolyPrinter 229 printer
How to safely set up and check the operation of the PolyPrinter 229 printer
How to set up Slicer for use with the 3D printer 
The correct 3D mesh files ( .OBJ, .STL ) for printing, and what resolution you need
How to download files from Thingiverse for printing
When to use special features to print such as rafts, brims, skirts, support material
How much infill to use, when, and why
What materials you can use to print on the PolyPrinter 229, and which must be avoided

You will need to bring
A pad of paper to take notesYour laptop ( Windows, Linux, or Mac )
Class Duration
One day, 2 hour course
Class Size
5 students

events.name: Ladies' Night: DIY Screenprinting
events.description:
In this workshop, we’ll briefly cover the history of the craft and then move on to practicalities. We’ll discuss stencil options and the characteristics of your process that will affect your final print. Everyone will create their own paper stencils and then practice printing on paper (greeting cards!), before printing on your choice of flour sack towels or tote bags. You’ll walk away with your stencil, your practice paper prints, and your textile prints. And you’ll have the knowledge to come back any time to do more screenprinting here, using CRAFT’s screens, squeegees, and inks.In this workshop, you will

make your own stencil,
choose your ink color,
practice printing on paper (greeting cards, anyone?),
choose textile items like towels and koozies to print your design on, and
learn in an intimate setting with one on one support as needed.

Drinks and snacks provided. 
All people who identify as women welcome.Reservations required. No kids. Workshops are refundable up to 72 hours in advance. 1 spot is for 1 person unless otherwise noted. 

Email hello [at] madeatcraft.com with questions.

events.description:
Join us at Patagonia Austin for the 2nd Annual Patagonia Harvest Festival for an evening of food and music, benefiting Farmshare Austin! Patagonia Harvest Fest is a collaboration of food from Patagonia Provisions and Farmshare Austin, focused on bringing the Austin community together and reminding us to think about where our food comes from. 

This year's dinner will be created and prepared by Austin rising star chef, Demmerick Johnson of Ladybird's Austin Kitchen. The menu features locally grown organic veggies from non-profit Farmshare Austin to accompany Patagonia Provisions. The dinner is family style and primarily vegetarian and pescatarian plus with the Chef's special pulled pork.

Doors open at 6:15pm, dinner starts at 7:30pm. Live music by Fiddlefish, an Austin Americana band. Beer by Hops and Grain + tasty non-alcoholic libations. Tickets start at $35 and includes 2 drinks, a multi-course meal and 1 raffle ticket. Raffle prizes include Patagonia and Farmshare swag! Extra raffle tickets and drinks will be available for purchase.
